<subSubSection lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="422" pageId="10" pageNumber="421" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,1513,2007]" pageId="10" pageNumber="421">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1621,1647]" pageId="10" pageNumber="421">Remarks.</emphasis>
Currently, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Becker" authorityYear="1902" box="[445,593,1621,1647]" class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Graphidaceae" genus="Schistostoma" kingdom="Fungi" order="Ostropales" pageId="10" pageNumber="421" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[445,593,1621,1647]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="421">Schistostoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a broadly defined, problematic genus sometimes hardly distinguishable from 
<taxonomicName box="[213,333,1657,1683]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Microphor" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="421" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[213,333,1657,1683]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="421">Microphor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Shamshev, I. V. &amp; Sinclair, B. J." box="[348,655,1657,1683]" pageId="10" pageNumber="421" pagination="335 - 346" refId="ref16072" refString="Shamshev, I. V. &amp; Sinclair, B. J. (2006) The genus Schistostoma Becker from southern Africa, with an evaluation of its generic status (Diptera: Dolichopodidae s. l.: Microphorinae). African Invertebrates, 47, 335 - 346." type="journal article" year="2006">Shamshev &amp; Sinclair 2006</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Brooks, S. E. &amp; Cumming, J. M." box="[666,963,1657,1683]" pageId="10" pageNumber="421" pagination="1 - 141" refId="ref13522" refString="Brooks, S. E. &amp; Cumming, J. M. (2022) Revision of the Nearctic Microphorinae (Diptera: Dolichopodidae sensu lato). Zootaxa, 5095 (1), 1 - 141. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 5095.1.1" type="journal article" year="2022">Brooks &amp; Cumming 2022</bibRefCitation>
). Provisionally, monophyly of this lineage of microphorines could be supported by the medial hypandrial prolongation of male terminalia (absent in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Microphor" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="421" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="421">Microphor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and by six or seven exposed female abdominal segments (five exposed segments in 
<taxonomicName box="[1178,1298,1729,1755]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Microphor" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="421" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1178,1298,1729,1755]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="421">Microphor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) (
<bibRefCitation author="Brooks, S. E. &amp; Cumming, J. M." pageId="10" pageNumber="421" pagination="1 - 141" refId="ref13522" refString="Brooks, S. E. &amp; Cumming, J. M. (2022) Revision of the Nearctic Microphorinae (Diptera: Dolichopodidae sensu lato). Zootaxa, 5095 (1), 1 - 141. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 5095.1.1" type="journal article" year="2022">Brooks &amp; Cumming 2022</bibRefCitation>
). It is evident that both these characters are not always easily-observable features, especially in fossils. In addition, the real number of exposed female abdominal segments may probably be difficult to distinguish sometimes due to pre-mortal behaviour and post-mortal changes of a specimen in semiliquid sticky resin (Martínez- Delclòs 
<emphasis box="[244,293,1873,1899]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="421">et al</emphasis>
. 2004; 
<bibRefCitation author="Arillo, A." box="[376,511,1873,1899]" pageId="10" pageNumber="421" pagination="159 - 166" refId="ref13327" refString="Arillo, A. (2007) Paleoethology: fossilized behaviours in amber. Geologica Acta, 5, 159 - 166." type="journal article" year="2007">Arillo 2007</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,1513,2007]" lastBlockId="11.[151,1436,151,285]" lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="422" pageId="10" pageNumber="421">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Becker" authorityYear="1902" box="[199,347,1909,1935]" class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Graphidaceae" genus="Schistostoma" kingdom="Fungi" order="Ostropales" pageId="10" pageNumber="421" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[199,347,1909,1935]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="421">Schistostoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
comprises 50 described extant and two extinct species. The recent species are distributed mostly in the Holarctic, although, three species are known from 
<collectingCountry box="[797,941,1945,1971]" name="South Africa" pageId="10" pageNumber="421">South Africa</collectingCountry>
and only one species from the Oriental Region (
<bibRefCitation author="Shamshev, I. V. &amp; Sinclair, B. J." box="[214,518,1981,2007]" pageId="10" pageNumber="421" pagination="335 - 346" refId="ref16072" refString="Shamshev, I. V. &amp; Sinclair, B. J. (2006) The genus Schistostoma Becker from southern Africa, with an evaluation of its generic status (Diptera: Dolichopodidae s. l.: Microphorinae). African Invertebrates, 47, 335 - 346." type="journal article" year="2006">Shamshev &amp; Sinclair 2006</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Shamshev, I. V." box="[528,709,1981,2007]" pageId="10" pageNumber="421" pagination="303 - 306" refId="ref16124" refString="Shamshev, I. V. (2020) First record of an extant species of the genus Schistostoma Becker (Diptera: Dolichopodidae: Microphorinae) from the Oriental Region. Russian Entomological Journal, 29 (3), 303 - 306. https: // doi. org / 10.15298 / rusentj. 29.3.11" type="journal article" year="2020">Shamshev 2020</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Brooks, S. E. &amp; Cumming, J. M." box="[719,1012,1981,2007]" pageId="10" pageNumber="421" pagination="1 - 141" refId="ref13522" refString="Brooks, S. E. &amp; Cumming, J. M. (2022) Revision of the Nearctic Microphorinae (Diptera: Dolichopodidae sensu lato). Zootaxa, 5095 (1), 1 - 141. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 5095.1.1" type="journal article" year="2022">Brooks &amp; Cumming 2022</bibRefCitation>
). Both extinct species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Becker" authorityYear="1902" box="[1288,1436,1981,2007]" class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Graphidaceae" genus="Schistostoma" kingdom="Fungi" order="Ostropales" pageId="10" pageNumber="421" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1288,1436,1981,2007]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="421">Schistostoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were described from Burmese amber and they have remarkably modified male forelegs, which is a unique feature within the genus and all fossil microphorines (
<bibRefCitation author="Brooks, S. E. &amp; Cumming, J. M. &amp; Grimaldi, D. A." box="[669,883,187,213]" pageId="11" pageNumber="422" pagination="121 - 131" refId="ref13574" refString="Brooks, S. E., Cumming, J. M. &amp; Grimaldi, D. A. (2019) Remarkable new fossil species of Schistostoma Becker (Diptera: Dolichopodidae: Microphorinae) from mid-Cretaceous Burmese amber. Zootaxa, 4624 (1), 121 - 131. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4624.1.8" type="journal article" year="2019">
Brooks 
<emphasis box="[759,808,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="422">et al</emphasis>
. 2019
</bibRefCitation>
). In addition, there is a well-preserved male of an undescribed species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Becker" authorityYear="1902" box="[414,562,223,249]" class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Graphidaceae" genus="Schistostoma" kingdom="Fungi" order="Ostropales" pageId="11" pageNumber="422" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[414,562,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="422">Schistostoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Rovno amber (Shamshev &amp; Perkovsky, unpubl. data). It is very similar habitually to the species from Burmese amber, but has simple legs.
</paragraph>
